WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:01:06.930
&gt;&gt; 

00:01:06.930 --> 00:01:08.560
At this time, it's my pleasure to welcome
Chitra back to Google again in 2010.

00:01:08.560 --> 00:01:10.230
I first met her -- let's see, I think I walked
into a class in Foothill

00:01:10.230 --> 00:01:12.000
College where she was teaching poetry.
And I studied with her for at least two quarters,

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:13.220
I think.
The fact that she was an excellent poet, and

00:01:13.220 --> 00:01:14.560
probably still is, has
been eclipsed a little bit because she's now

00:01:14.560 --> 00:01:16.110
much more famous as a
novelist and has at least 16 books to her

00:01:16.110 --> 00:01:17.110
credit.
Not only has she completed the books, but

00:01:17.110 --> 00:01:18.330
her books have won several
awards including the American Book Award,

00:01:18.330 --> 00:01:19.550
several PEN awards,
the O. Henry and Pushcart Prizes, and two

00:01:19.550 --> 00:01:20.550
of her novels have been
filmed.

00:01:20.550 --> 00:01:21.550
She's also a professor of creative writing
at the University of Houston.

00:01:21.550 --> 00:01:23.110
Last year when she was here, she read from
her book, The Palace of

00:01:23.110 --> 00:01:24.110
Illusions.
Today, she's back with a brand new novel,

00:01:24.110 --> 00:01:25.440
One Amazing Thing.
One Amazing Thing is set in an unnamed American

00:01:25.440 --> 00:01:27.110
city, but I noted that
it was a city that has cable cars and earthquakes.

00:01:27.110 --> 00:01:28.110
So, maybe unnamed is not exactly a complete
surprise.

00:01:28.110 --> 00:01:29.550
So this novel winds together the personal
stories of individuals who have been

00:01:29.550 --> 00:01:30.990
thrown together in unexpected circumstances.
And we're going to welcome Chitra here to

00:01:30.990 --> 00:01:31.990
describe it and read from it.

00:01:31.990 --> 00:01:32.990
[applause]

00:01:32.990 --> 00:01:36.540
Chitra Divakaruni: Thank you, Ross.
It's a real pleasure to be back here at Google.

00:01:36.540 --> 00:01:41.860
I enjoyed my last visit very much and I'm
already enjoying this visit a

00:01:41.860 --> 00:01:45.220
great deal.
And I'm hoping that after I talk, we'll have

00:01:45.220 --> 00:01:50.750
a conversation as well.
So I'm going to be talking to you about this

00:01:50.750 --> 00:01:56.710
new novel which has just
come out, just a few days back, so you are

00:01:56.710 --> 00:02:00.570
one of the first people that
I'll be talking to about this novel.

00:02:00.570 --> 00:02:07.420
And as you heard from Ross, it's a novel about
people who are in a

00:02:07.420 --> 00:02:14.220
life-threatening situation.
A group of people, all of them strangers to

00:02:14.220 --> 00:02:20.590
each other, go to an Indian
consulate to get visas to go to India.

00:02:20.590 --> 00:02:23.130
They all want to go to India for different
reasons.

00:02:23.130 --> 00:02:26.450
And in the beginning of the novel, we don't
know why they want to go to

00:02:26.450 --> 00:02:30.239
India, but as the novel goes on that will
be revealed.

00:02:30.239 --> 00:02:35.170
But while they are there waiting for their
visas, seven of them, and

00:02:35.170 --> 00:02:39.470
two visa office workers, a major earthquake
strikes.

00:02:39.470 --> 00:02:43.120
And now they're trapped in the basement of
this building, which has

00:02:43.120 --> 00:02:51.700
partially collapsed on them, around them.
And they try very hard to get out but they

00:02:51.700 --> 00:02:56.110
can't.
And this book -- which is very different from

00:02:56.110 --> 00:02:59.820
all of my other books,
which often deal with the immigrant situation

00:02:59.820 --> 00:03:04.420
and people from India
living here or stories that are set in India

00:03:04.420 --> 00:03:09.060
or the movement back and
forth between East and West -- this one is

00:03:09.060 --> 00:03:13.030
very different.
It's a tale of surviving under really difficult

00:03:13.030 --> 00:03:17.970
circumstances.
And the way I came to write this book is quite

00:03:17.970 --> 00:03:22.880
interesting.
But before that, I wanted to say that my entire

00:03:22.880 --> 00:03:26.790
tour for One Amazing
Thing, including this event, is dedicated

00:03:26.790 --> 00:03:29.340
to the memory of my mother
who passed away recently.

00:03:29.340 --> 00:03:33.830
My mother's name is Mrs. [INAUDIBLE] Banerjee
and she always wanted to

00:03:33.830 --> 00:03:38.919
be a writer herself but because of the time
and place where she grew

00:03:38.919 --> 00:03:43.989
up, she wasn't able to do that.
In her 60s, she did write a few memoir pieces

00:03:43.989 --> 00:03:46.070
that were published in
magazines.

00:03:46.070 --> 00:03:50.380
But she always read everything I wrote, and
she was very supportive.

00:03:50.380 --> 00:03:56.170
Now, like people, many people of her generation,
my mother was not very

00:03:56.170 --> 00:04:00.329
effusive about expressing how she felt about
things.

00:04:00.329 --> 00:04:04.310
So I would ask her, "Well, Mom, you read this
book.

00:04:04.310 --> 00:04:09.651
What did you think?"
And she would generally say, "Hmmm," which

00:04:09.651 --> 00:04:14.639
meant it was okay.
But when she read "One Amazing Thing", which

00:04:14.639 --> 00:04:19.239
she read sometime -- I was
able to get her an advanced copy before she

00:04:19.239 --> 00:04:24.070
passed away, she said, in
my language Bengali, she said, "PAULOWE"(sic),

00:04:24.070 --> 00:04:28.340
which means "not bad."
So I felt that was like high praise coming

00:04:28.340 --> 00:04:32.740
from my mother.
So I'm very excited about this book.

00:04:32.740 --> 00:04:36.400
I feel it must be my best book if my mother
said that.

00:04:36.400 --> 00:04:43.460
Anyway, but how did I come to write this book?
Sometimes books begin writing themselves before

00:04:43.460 --> 00:04:46.960
you're ready for them,
and that is what happened with One Amazing

00:04:46.960 --> 00:04:50.180
Thing.
Now, although I used to live in the Bay Area

00:04:50.180 --> 00:04:54.270
for many years and
certainly experienced my share of earthquakes

00:04:54.270 --> 00:04:58.060
while I was here, this
book actually comes out of a very different

00:04:58.060 --> 00:05:02.780
experience.
I live now in Houston, and some years back,

00:05:02.780 --> 00:05:08.210
you know when Katrina hit
New Orleans, well, a lot of Katrina refugees

00:05:08.210 --> 00:05:11.930
came to Houston.
And I was volunteering in one of the centers

00:05:11.930 --> 00:05:14.340
where we helped the
refugees.

00:05:14.340 --> 00:05:18.210
And I began to notice something interesting,
which is I would be

00:05:18.210 --> 00:05:23.390
dealing with many people who had all undergone
the same experience

00:05:23.390 --> 00:05:28.479
pretty much, and pretty much they'd lost everything.
They'd lost their homes.

00:05:28.479 --> 00:05:32.120
They'd lost, sometimes, their pets.
You know, everything was gone.

00:05:32.120 --> 00:05:39.039
But their responses were very different.
Some people were very angry, some people were

00:05:39.039 --> 00:05:44.289
very bitter, and some
people were, kind of accepting of it.

00:05:44.289 --> 00:05:45.289
And they would even you know, they were appreciative
that they were

00:05:45.289 --> 00:05:47.639
being helped.
They would even joke about things.

00:05:47.639 --> 00:05:51.870
And I began to think, well, what is it that
allows people to -- when

00:05:51.870 --> 00:05:56.740
they're all in that same life-threatening
situation, when they've all

00:05:56.740 --> 00:06:00.960
faced catastrophes, how is it that some of
them can be so much more

00:06:00.960 --> 00:06:05.979
graceful about accepting what has happened,
and why can't everyone do

00:06:05.979 --> 00:06:08.539
that?
Why is that that there's this difference?

00:06:08.539 --> 00:06:13.069
Well, just a few weeks later, another hurricane
approached.

00:06:13.069 --> 00:06:16.689
And this time it was Hurricane Rita.
It was coming right at Houston.

00:06:16.689 --> 00:06:20.830
So everyone was very nervous and the authorities
evacuated us.

00:06:20.830 --> 00:06:25.949
But as you can imagine when, you know, all
that many people are all

00:06:25.949 --> 00:06:30.740
evacuated at the same time, we all got on
the freeways, but then we

00:06:30.740 --> 00:06:34.099
weren't going anywhere.
The freeways were completely jammed.

00:06:34.099 --> 00:06:39.139
And so I was sitting on Interstate 10, with
like hundreds of cars

00:06:39.139 --> 00:06:44.480
around me, all of us not going anywhere and
Rita was coming.

00:06:44.480 --> 00:06:48.210
And fortunately, at the last minute Rita decided
to take a little

00:06:48.210 --> 00:06:51.759
detour otherwise I wouldn't be here and this
book wouldn't be here

00:06:51.759 --> 00:06:56.169
either today.
But as I was experiencing all of that panic

00:06:56.169 --> 00:07:00.780
and fear, I began to notice
the same kind of responses around me.

00:07:00.780 --> 00:07:03.819
Some people were really upset.
They were angry.

00:07:03.819 --> 00:07:09.699
They were getting into fights with each other.
It was -- you know, they were like, I'm going

00:07:09.699 --> 00:07:11.370
to survive no matter
what.

00:07:11.370 --> 00:07:14.300
And what I have to do to do it.
And other people were very compassionate.

00:07:14.300 --> 00:07:20.979
They were sharing whatever food and water
they had with other people.

00:07:20.979 --> 00:07:24.030
They were helping people who were feeling
sick.

00:07:24.030 --> 00:07:26.860
And I noticed that whole spectrum one more
time.

00:07:26.860 --> 00:07:30.910
And I started thinking, you know, I really
want to explore this.

00:07:30.910 --> 00:07:35.090
I want to write about this.
Because in everyone's life, we're going to

00:07:35.090 --> 00:07:37.249
face situations of
catastrophe.

00:07:37.249 --> 00:07:42.430
They might not be natural disasters, but we're
all going to be in places

00:07:42.430 --> 00:07:46.460
where we have no control over what happens,
and we're frightened, and

00:07:46.460 --> 00:07:51.550
you know, we're worried and we're anxious
and we're scared.

00:07:51.550 --> 00:07:55.139
And we need to know how to deal with these
situations.

00:07:55.139 --> 00:08:00.280
So here we have these nine people and they're
in that situation, and at

00:08:00.280 --> 00:08:06.810
first they begin to panic.
But then they're going to find a way to deal

00:08:06.810 --> 00:08:09.779
with where they're at
because they can't get out of there.

00:08:09.779 --> 00:08:13.039
And that becomes the story of One Amazing
Thing.

00:08:13.039 --> 00:08:16.610
So I thought I would read to you a little
bit from maybe two different

00:08:16.610 --> 00:08:26.469
sections, and then throw it open for questions.
So this novel is different from my other novels,

00:08:26.469 --> 00:08:32.300
also, in that in most
of my other novels, all of the main characters

00:08:32.300 --> 00:08:38.570
are Indian.
But here, I wanted a community of many different

00:08:38.570 --> 00:08:40.240
people of many
different backgrounds.

00:08:40.240 --> 00:08:46.640
And that's what we have here.
So there are people -- so in that visa office,

00:08:46.640 --> 00:08:50.110
all getting ready to go
to India for different reasons.

00:08:50.110 --> 00:08:56.460
There's an African-American ex-solider; there's
an older white couple;

00:08:56.460 --> 00:09:03.230
there's an old Chinese woman with her young
 -- with her granddaughter

00:09:03.230 --> 00:09:08.120
who was a teenager and who is kind of punk,
Goth.

00:09:08.120 --> 00:09:12.740
And there's a Muslim-American man.
There are just all kinds of people and one

00:09:12.740 --> 00:09:17.140
of -- and what's different is
they're all the main characters.

00:09:17.140 --> 00:09:21.960
Unlike my other novels, there isn't like one
protagonist or two.

00:09:21.960 --> 00:09:26.370
Everyone is important.
And what they begin doing as the novel goes

00:09:26.370 --> 00:09:28.420
on is going to be equally
important.

00:09:28.420 --> 00:09:32.750
So I'm going to read to you a little bit from
the beginning.

00:09:32.750 --> 00:09:42.790
And in the beginning of -- here's we're in
the point of view of Uma,

00:09:42.790 --> 00:09:49.230
who is a graduate student, and she studies
literature at the university,

00:09:49.230 --> 00:09:54.190
and she's brought her book which she's been
studying The Canterbury

00:09:54.190 --> 00:09:59.050
Tales, which as you probably know, is a story
set in a very different

00:09:59.050 --> 00:10:05.180
time, but tales within tales.
And she's reading that.

00:10:05.180 --> 00:10:08.839
Okay.
"And as -- and she's waiting to be called.

00:10:08.839 --> 00:10:13.570
She came here thinking that she would be given
a 9 o'clock appointment,

00:10:13.570 --> 00:10:17.959
but 9 o'clock came, and 10 o'clock came, and
11 o'clock came -- and if

00:10:17.959 --> 00:10:22.959
you've had any experience with bureaucratic
offices, this often happens

00:10:22.959 --> 00:10:26.710
and now it's afternoon.
And there are all these other -- six other

00:10:26.710 --> 00:10:31.880
people waiting with her.
And she wants to call her boyfriend, Ramon,

00:10:31.880 --> 00:10:39.740
to tell him where she's at
because she has not -- she has not told him

00:10:39.740 --> 00:10:43.629
where she's coming, for
reasons that will be clarified later on.

00:10:43.629 --> 00:10:49.560
So she's walking around the room trying to
get reception, but she's not

00:10:49.560 --> 00:10:54.870
getting cell phone reception.
Phone to her ear, Uma took a few steps forward.

00:10:54.870 --> 00:11:02.460
It felt good to stretch her legs.
The phone gave a small burp against her ear,

00:11:02.460 --> 00:11:06.260
but before she could check
if it was working, the rumble rose through

00:11:06.260 --> 00:11:11.480
the floor.
This time there was no mistaking it's intention.

00:11:11.480 --> 00:11:15.610
It was as though a giant had placed his mouth
against the building's

00:11:15.610 --> 00:11:22.370
foundation and roared.
The floor buckled, throwing Uma to the ground.

00:11:22.370 --> 00:11:27.009
The giant took the building in both his hands
and shook it.

00:11:27.009 --> 00:11:32.170
A chair flew across the room toward Uma.
She raised her left hand to shield herself.

00:11:32.170 --> 00:11:36.730
The chair crashed into her wrist and a pain
worse than anything she had

00:11:36.730 --> 00:11:41.300
known surged through her arm.
People were screaming.

00:11:41.300 --> 00:11:47.860
Feet ran by her, then ran back again.
She tried to wedge herself beneath one of

00:11:47.860 --> 00:11:52.620
the chairs, as she had been
taught long ago in grade school, but only

00:11:52.620 --> 00:11:54.360
her head and shoulders would
fit.

00:11:54.360 --> 00:12:00.170
The cell phone was still in her other hand,
pressed against her ear.

00:12:00.170 --> 00:12:04.769
Was that Ramon's voice asking her to leave
a message or was it just her

00:12:04.769 --> 00:12:11.190
need to hear him?
Above her, the ceiling collapsed in an explosion

00:12:11.190 --> 00:12:15.970
of plaster.
Beams broke apart with the sound of gigantic

00:12:15.970 --> 00:12:19.509
bones snapping.
A light fixture shattered.

00:12:19.509 --> 00:12:25.980
For a moment, before the electricity failed,
she saw the glowing

00:12:25.980 --> 00:12:31.370
filaments of the naked bulb.
Rubble fell through the blackness, burying

00:12:31.370 --> 00:12:35.140
her legs.
Her arm was on fire.

00:12:35.140 --> 00:12:39.699
She cradled it against her chest, a useless
gesture, when she would

00:12:39.699 --> 00:12:45.459
probably die in the next minute.
Was that the sound of running water?

00:12:45.459 --> 00:12:50.589
Was the basement they were in flooding?
She thought she heard a beep.

00:12:50.589 --> 00:12:57.420
The machine ready to record her voice.
'Ramon', she cried, her mouth full of dust.

00:12:57.420 --> 00:13:01.620
She thought of his long meticulous fingers,
how they could fix anything

00:13:01.620 --> 00:13:05.190
she broke.
She thought of the small red moles on his

00:13:05.190 --> 00:13:08.509
chest just above the left
nipple.

00:13:08.509 --> 00:13:12.610
She wanted to say something important and
consoling, something for him

00:13:12.610 --> 00:13:18.329
to remember her by.
But she could think of nothing and then her

00:13:18.329 --> 00:13:23.160
phone went dead."
So the earthquake has struck and now this

00:13:23.160 --> 00:13:27.880
whole group will be shut up
in this place, things are going to get really

00:13:27.880 --> 00:13:32.449
bad.
Bits of the ceiling keep falling on them and

00:13:32.449 --> 00:13:36.069
they think there's going
to be an aftershock that will cause more of

00:13:36.069 --> 00:13:40.390
the building to collapse.
And then water starts rising in the basement,

00:13:40.390 --> 00:13:43.701
and they're panicking
and they're behaving badly towards each other

00:13:43.701 --> 00:13:49.180
and they're fighting.
And after a really bad fight, Uma says to

00:13:49.180 --> 00:13:53.680
the others, well, we can kind
of destroy ourselves this way or we can do

00:13:53.680 --> 00:13:56.230
something more positive with
our time.

00:13:56.230 --> 00:13:59.769
And she says, why don't we tell each other
 -- while we're hopefully

00:13:59.769 --> 00:14:04.850
waiting for rescue -- why don't we tell each
other a story out of our

00:14:04.850 --> 00:14:09.670
lives, something we've never told anyone.
Something really important.

00:14:09.670 --> 00:14:14.529
And everyone is kind of against this idea.
You know, there're not in any mood to tell

00:14:14.529 --> 00:14:17.759
stories.
But Uma says, it's, it's really important.

00:14:17.759 --> 00:14:23.170
It will take our minds off of what's happening
and it will help us get

00:14:23.170 --> 00:14:26.170
to know each other.
Well, one of them says well, I don't have

00:14:26.170 --> 00:14:31.160
a story to tell and then Uma
says in everyone's life there's at least One

00:14:31.160 --> 00:14:34.569
Amazing Thing.
Think about what is yours.

00:14:34.569 --> 00:14:41.610
And then slowly, people begin to tell stories.
And one of the ideas that I had when I was

00:14:41.610 --> 00:14:47.050
writing this novel is that I
really believe that in all of our lives, there's

00:14:47.050 --> 00:14:50.930
something special,
something unusual, something that is amazing.

00:14:50.930 --> 00:14:56.279
But because we're so busy with our everyday
life, doing our daily

00:14:56.279 --> 00:15:02.160
things, taking care of everyday responsibilities,
we forget that we

00:15:02.160 --> 00:15:06.670
have these things that have happened to us,
that have really made us

00:15:06.670 --> 00:15:10.361
who we are today.
So it's my hope that as people read this book,

00:15:10.361 --> 00:15:15.100
they will start thinking
about what is One Amazing Thing that they

00:15:15.100 --> 00:15:19.370
had in their lives.
If they had only one story they could tell,

00:15:19.370 --> 00:15:24.750
what would they talk about?
And now I'll read to you about -- from one

00:15:24.750 --> 00:15:30.889
of these stories, where
there's a woman who works in the visa office

00:15:30.889 --> 00:15:35.240
who is trapped here, and
she's telling a story about when she was in

00:15:35.240 --> 00:15:38.050
India.
And the story will kind of tell us how she

00:15:38.050 --> 00:15:41.279
ended up in the visa office,
but I'll just read to you a little bit.

00:15:41.279 --> 00:15:46.129
One of my challenges in writing this book
was to get -- there are nine

00:15:46.129 --> 00:15:49.399
characters, there are going to be nine different
stories, and I wanted

00:15:49.399 --> 00:15:54.160
to make sure that each story had its own voice,
that you really got a

00:15:54.160 --> 00:16:00.889
sense of the character through the story.
And this character, her name is Malathi, and

00:16:00.889 --> 00:16:07.560
her name is Malathi, and
she's going to tell her story.

00:16:07.560 --> 00:16:13.129
"When I failed tenth grade for the second
time, my parents figured it

00:16:13.129 --> 00:16:19.340
was no use wasting more money on my school
fees and decided to marry me

00:16:19.340 --> 00:16:21.889
off.
I had no objections.

00:16:21.889 --> 00:16:24.470
It was not as though I had anything else to
do.

00:16:24.470 --> 00:16:28.930
Having navigated their way through the weddings
of two daughters

00:16:28.930 --> 00:16:34.490
already, my parents knew that the local matchmaker
would ask for a

00:16:34.490 --> 00:16:38.310
photograph.
If they could provide her with one in which

00:16:38.310 --> 00:16:43.720
I looked better than
normal, my chances of finding a husband, and

00:16:43.720 --> 00:16:48.399
theirs of negotiating a
smaller dowry, would be highly improved.

00:16:48.399 --> 00:16:53.770
Though in general, thrifty and suspicious,
they knew the importance of

00:16:53.770 --> 00:17:00.070
a well-chosen investment.
That is how I ended up in Miss Lola's Lovely

00:17:00.070 --> 00:17:03.940
Ladies salon, the premier
beauty shop in Coimbatore.

00:17:03.940 --> 00:17:12.510
My mother had been to Lovely Ladies only twice,
but Miss Lola knew her

00:17:12.510 --> 00:17:15.750
right away.
'The bridal photo special, again?' She asked.

00:17:15.750 --> 00:17:20.370
When my mother nodded, Ms. Lola looked me
looked me up and down and

00:17:20.370 --> 00:17:24.920
pronounced that I would require more work
than my sisters.

00:17:24.920 --> 00:17:29.120
My mother gave a sigh but did not disagree,
and the two of them fell to

00:17:29.120 --> 00:17:36.300
bargaining about the price of my beautification.
When they had reached an agreement, Miss Lola

00:17:36.300 --> 00:17:41.260
gave a volley of staccato
instructions to the pink-uniformed girls who

00:17:41.260 --> 00:17:46.940
worked for her, ending
with, bridal special, silver level, with hair

00:17:46.940 --> 00:17:52.410
oil.
Two girls whisked me to an inner sanctum filled

00:17:52.410 --> 00:18:00.680
with elegant women undergoing the complex
and painful process of improving upon nature.

00:18:00.680 --> 00:18:05.700
I was settled into a reclining chair and shrouded
in cotton sheets.

00:18:05.700 --> 00:18:10.660
And it was here in this moist, air conditioned
room, fragrant with

00:18:10.660 --> 00:18:15.890
astonishing and exotic substances which my
naive nose was incapable of

00:18:15.890 --> 00:18:21.910
identifying that I saw, as though illuminated
by lightening, the path

00:18:21.910 --> 00:18:28.520
of my future.
Until this day, I had thought of marriage

00:18:28.520 --> 00:18:33.450
as an inevitable destination,
the only choice a girl from a middle class

00:18:33.450 --> 00:18:39.280
Brahmin family, handicapped
by respectability, had in our sleepy town

00:18:39.280 --> 00:18:44.310
was to teach at the
Street Botnaverti Girls Higher Secondary School.

00:18:44.310 --> 00:18:50.530
But teachers were meagerly paid and resembled
chewed up sticks of sugar

00:18:50.530 --> 00:18:58.910
cane, and I had no desire to become one.
I confess, sometimes from our veranda, I spied

00:18:58.910 --> 00:19:04.060
on other kinds of women,
receptionists and typists who worked for Indian

00:19:04.060 --> 00:19:08.950
Oil or Guardbridge and
waited across from our house for the company

00:19:08.950 --> 00:19:14.260
vans to pick them up.
Torn between disapproval and envy, I noted

00:19:14.260 --> 00:19:19.090
the dresses that exposed
their knees, the shoes with platform heels,

00:19:19.090 --> 00:19:24.790
their permed hair.
They wore lipstick, even in daytime, erupted

00:19:24.790 --> 00:19:30.170
in laughter at frequent
intervals, whispered prodigiously when men

00:19:30.170 --> 00:19:34.900
in expensive cars drove by
and ignored the remarks aimed their way by

00:19:34.900 --> 00:19:40.460
lesser males.
But they were Kerala Christians, members of

00:19:40.460 --> 00:19:45.490
a forbidden, scandalous
species that I could never join.

00:19:45.490 --> 00:19:50.910
Lola's girls, though, with their perfectly
arched eyebrows, glowing

00:19:50.910 --> 00:19:56.060
skin, and pretty faces hanging over me like
radiant moons, were

00:19:56.060 --> 00:20:00.330
different.
As they plucked and exfoliated and massaged

00:20:00.330 --> 00:20:06.050
oil and pinched blackheads
and slathered my cheeks with Fair and Lovely

00:20:06.050 --> 00:20:10.350
cream, clucking soothingly
when I yelped, and assuring me that the end

00:20:10.350 --> 00:20:14.250
result would be worth it, I
felt a strange kinship with them.

00:20:14.250 --> 00:20:20.650
They camouflaged me with sufficient foundation,
face powder, kohl,

00:20:20.650 --> 00:20:26.350
lipstick, blush, and Vatika pure coconut hair
oil to pass as one of

00:20:26.350 --> 00:20:31.630
Lola's Lovely Ladies.
They attached a glistening bindi to my forehead

00:20:31.630 --> 00:20:33.930
and clipped fake
diamond earrings to my ears.

00:20:33.930 --> 00:20:40.000
