that so much of our life is based on destiny,

00:36:31.029 --> 00:36:32.710
and therefore we should
be more accepting?

00:36:32.710 --> 00:36:38.339
Well, I think we do see that and I do touch
on that a little bit.

00:36:38.339 --> 00:36:43.319
Although, the Indian characters -- well, the
younger ones, have grown

00:36:43.319 --> 00:36:47.780
up in this country, so you know, they're much
more Western in their

00:36:47.780 --> 00:36:50.630
thinking.
But there is a certain, the older characters

00:36:50.630 --> 00:36:54.430
have a certain feeling
that yes, this is destiny and it will work

00:36:54.430 --> 00:36:57.009
out the way it's meant to
work out.

00:36:57.009 --> 00:37:00.269
And they're much more -- you know, they're
much calmer.

00:37:00.269 --> 00:37:04.309
And I've left it to the reader to think is
that better or is that

00:37:04.309 --> 00:37:07.070
worse.
I mean, should we try really hard to change

00:37:07.070 --> 00:37:11.250
what's around us?
Or when we think it can't be changed, should

00:37:11.250 --> 00:37:12.980
we be peaceful and
accepting?

00:37:12.980 --> 00:37:16.359
But that comes up as a theme, so it's very
interesting that you should

00:37:16.359 --> 00:37:18.920
mention it.
Actually, when I was writing this book, I

00:37:18.920 --> 00:37:24.369
did a lot of research on
disasters and how people respond to disasters.

00:37:24.369 --> 00:37:29.369
And I noticed that, for example, when the
tsunami hit India, the

00:37:29.369 --> 00:37:36.740
responses were much more accepting and fate-oriented
than in Western

00:37:36.740 --> 00:37:39.460
catastrophes.
So there is that component.

00:37:39.460 --> 00:37:44.160
Ultimately, my belief, though, is that it's
personality-based.

00:37:44.160 --> 00:37:47.920
Some people believe in that more, and some
people might come from that

00:37:47.920 --> 00:37:56.869
culture, but they're much more individualistic.

00:37:56.869 --> 00:37:57.869
Yes?

00:37:57.869 --> 00:38:03.259
&gt;&gt; [INAUDIBLE]

00:38:03.259 --> 00:38:30.310
Chitra Divakaruni: Yeah.
The question, that again is an interesting

00:38:30.310 --> 00:38:32.549
question, looking at
cultural difference.

00:38:32.549 --> 00:38:37.140
When in Mumbai, you're talking about the rain
and the floods and people

00:38:37.140 --> 00:38:40.690
were very worried they were extremely helpful
towards each other.

00:38:40.690 --> 00:38:48.529
In fact, more so than in usual times.
And when I was researching, I read in a number

00:38:48.529 --> 00:38:54.809
of places that often
disasters will bring out the best in a community,

00:38:54.809 --> 00:38:59.380
and I think this
happens, especially in communities that are

00:38:59.380 --> 00:39:04.859
more community-oriented or
family-oriented, so I think that was the case

00:39:04.859 --> 00:39:11.079
in Mumbai, where people
saw the people who were suffering as part

00:39:11.079 --> 00:39:14.140
of this larger family that
they had to take care of.

00:39:14.140 --> 00:39:17.490
And in fact, there are many really heartwarming
stories of that point.

00:39:17.490 --> 00:39:21.700
And there was very little in terms of violence
or looting or anything

00:39:21.700 --> 00:39:25.099
of that kind.
In Houston, I saw both kinds.

00:39:25.099 --> 00:39:28.970
You know, I saw people who were very kind
to each other.

00:39:28.970 --> 00:39:32.170
I remember we were all stuck on the freeway,
and then we were moved off

00:39:32.170 --> 00:39:35.630
the freeway onto the side roads in little
towns, and we'd go through

00:39:35.630 --> 00:39:39.019
towns and they'd have a sign up on their porch
saying, do you need

00:39:39.019 --> 00:39:41.069
water?
Do you need to use the restroom?

00:39:41.069 --> 00:39:45.470
Come into our house.
And this is to strangers.

00:39:45.470 --> 00:39:48.580
And on the other hand, there were people like
don't come near me.

00:39:48.580 --> 00:39:53.430
Don't even, you know, look at me.
So there was this whole spectrum.

00:39:53.430 --> 00:40:00.630
And I really think perhaps it came out of
what people thought of

00:40:00.630 --> 00:40:04.000
community.
People who were very individualistic, perhaps

00:40:04.000 --> 00:40:07.720
they were like, I'm going
to survive no matter what happens to you.

00:40:07.720 --> 00:40:11.859
And then others were like, yes, I want to
survive but at what cost?

00:40:11.859 --> 00:40:15.569
I don't want to lose my humanity in order
to survive.

00:40:15.569 --> 00:40:20.710
And that's kind of, one of the themes in "One
Amazing Thing".

00:40:20.710 --> 00:40:25.589
In the beginning, everyone here, too, is very
concerned about their

00:40:25.589 --> 00:40:28.519
personal survival, but at a certain point
they begin to think, no,

00:40:28.519 --> 00:40:34.319
we're a community.
We rise or we fall together.

00:40:34.319 --> 00:40:38.380
And they become more much concerned with everyone's
welfare, which, of

00:40:38.380 --> 00:40:45.420
course is, I think, is what we kind of need
to learn as human beings, that yes, we want

00:40:45.420 --> 00:40:53.480
to survive but not at the cost of losing our
humanity.

00:40:53.480 --> 00:40:54.480
[PAUSE]

00:40:54.480 --> 00:40:57.519
Final questions?

00:40:57.519 --> 00:40:58.519
Yes?

00:40:58.519 --> 00:41:08.390
&gt;&gt; [INAUDIBLE]

00:41:08.390 --> 00:41:33.450
Chitra Divakaruni: The question is that if
you're a writer, but you're

00:41:33.450 --> 00:41:38.320
just starting out, you haven't been published
yet, how do you get to

00:41:38.320 --> 00:41:42.529
that point?
And there is a question that comes a little

00:41:42.529 --> 00:41:46.869
ahead, and that may be your
question, too, or maybe you've passed that

00:41:46.869 --> 00:41:51.440
stage, which is that when you
have a full time demanding job but you really

00:41:51.440 --> 00:41:55.829
want to write and you
feel this desire and need to create something,

00:41:55.829 --> 00:42:00.970
how do you do that?
I mean, how do you make time to do that?

00:42:00.970 --> 00:42:04.660
Because, you know, you have to give writing
or any art if you're

00:42:04.660 --> 00:42:08.920
serious about it, you have to give it time,
you have to give it energy,

00:42:08.920 --> 00:42:15.420
and that's -- that's a real trick.
I mean, it's difficult to find time, to carve

00:42:15.420 --> 00:42:21.420
out that time to give to
your writing, so that you can research, you

00:42:21.420 --> 00:42:25.509
can write, you can revise.
You can really make the piece the best it

00:42:25.509 --> 00:42:29.920
can be.
And I think, what I tell my students often

00:42:29.920 --> 00:42:32.680
is that we have to start
prioritizing.

00:42:32.680 --> 00:42:38.339
We have to cut some things out of our lives.
And we have to save that time and put it into

00:42:38.339 --> 00:42:42.119
our writing.
And we have to create a schedule and then

00:42:42.119 --> 00:42:46.619
stick to it, the way we stick
to our work schedules we have to stick to

00:42:46.619 --> 00:42:48.640
our writing schedules as
well.

00:42:48.640 --> 00:42:53.400
And everyone will have to decide for themselves
how many hours a week,

00:42:53.400 --> 00:42:58.700
for example, can I give to my writing?
But you have to -- once you make that decision

00:42:58.700 --> 00:42:59.910
 -- you have to stick to
it.

00:42:59.910 --> 00:43:03.609
And one of the things that I discovered because
it was the same with me

00:43:03.609 --> 00:43:07.589
I was teaching full-time.
I had two children, I was doing community

00:43:07.589 --> 00:43:11.460
work.
There was just a lot on my plate as well.

00:43:11.460 --> 00:43:16.200
But I decided that well, I can cut out this
and this and this and then

00:43:16.200 --> 00:43:19.780
I have these many hours, and I'm not going
to do anything else with

00:43:19.780 --> 00:43:21.029
them.
I'm going to write.

00:43:21.029 --> 00:43:24.400
So each one, I think, we have to decide what
we can give up.

00:43:24.400 --> 00:43:27.680
All right, so now we've done that, we've given
up the time and we have

00:43:27.680 --> 00:43:31.829
a manuscript.
We've shared it with some people who know

00:43:31.829 --> 00:43:35.539
about writing, so they've given us good feedback,
we've revised.

00:43:35.539 --> 00:43:40.170
Now what do we do?
Well the way it is in America, is if you are

00:43:40.170 --> 00:43:44.069
a fiction writer
particularly, have you to find an agent.

00:43:44.069 --> 00:43:48.279
So that would be my advice to you would be
to research agents.

00:43:48.279 --> 00:43:52.690
And one good way to research is to look at
the people who's writing you

00:43:52.690 --> 00:43:57.299
like, and who you think are writing things
similar to what you're

00:43:57.299 --> 00:44:02.349
writing, and see who their agents are.
And their agents will often be mentioned.

00:44:02.349 --> 00:44:06.680
You can probably Google it and find out who
their agents are or in

00:44:06.680 --> 00:44:09.869
their books they sometimes acknowledge their
agents, like I always

00:44:09.869 --> 00:44:14.789
thank my agents in my books.
And then you would go and the agents would

00:44:14.789 --> 00:44:20.690
have websites, they'll have,
you know, they'll give you pointers as to

00:44:20.690 --> 00:44:23.839
how to submit to them and you
should send stuff.

00:44:23.839 --> 00:44:27.710
But without agents, it's very hard now in
America to get your work to

00:44:27.710 --> 00:44:32.299
be looked at seriously by good publishers.
So that's what I would say.

00:44:32.299 --> 00:44:34.779
